Development of a Biomarker Signature using Grating coupled Fluorescence Plasmonic Microarray for diagnosis of MIS-C

Microbiome data analysis

Load all necessary packages. pacman will install and load any missing packages.

if (!require("pacman")) install.packages("pacman")
## Loading required package: pacman
pacman::p_load(decontam, phyloseq, BiocManager, qiime2R, DESeq2, tidyverse, RColorBrewer, viridis, vegan, pheatmap, ggplot2, patchwork, ggpubr, ranacapa, nlme, compositions, readr, devtools, microViz, ANCOMBC, microbiome, GUniFrac, scales, DT)

Use the Qiime2R plugin to import .qza files from Qiime2 into phyloseq.

phy = qza_to_phyloseq("filtered-table.qza", "rooted-tree.qza", "taxonomy.qza", "metadata.txt",tmp = "C:/tmp")

Replace underscores in the taxonomy with spaces (e.g.Escherichia_coli becomes Escherichia coli).

phy@tax_table = gsub("_", " ", phy@tax_table)

Use negative controls to identify and remove likely contaminants.

sample_data(phy)$is.neg <- sample_data(phy)$Sample_or_Control == "Control Sample"
contamdf.prev <- isContaminant(phy, method="prevalence", neg="is.neg")
## Warning in .is_contaminant(seqtab, conc = conc, neg = neg, method = method, :
## Removed 1 samples with zero total counts (or frequency).

## Warning in .is_contaminant(seqtab, conc = conc, neg = neg, method = method, :
## Removed 1 samples with zero total counts (or frequency).
table(contamdf.prev$contaminant)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 11646     6
phy.pa <- transform_sample_counts(phy, function(abund) 1*(abund>0))
phy.pa.neg <- prune_samples(sample_data(phy.pa)$Sample_or_Control == "Control Sample", phy.pa)
phy.pa.pos <- prune_samples(sample_data(phy.pa)$Sample_or_Control == "True Sample", phy.pa)
df.pa <- data.frame(pa.pos=taxa_sums(phy.pa.pos), pa.neg=taxa_sums(phy.pa.neg),
                      contaminant=contamdf.prev$contaminant)
ggplot(data=df.pa, aes(x=pa.neg, y=pa.pos, color=contaminant)) + geom_point() +
  xlab("Prevalence (Negative Controls)") + ylab("Prevalence (True Samples)")

phy <- prune_taxa(!contamdf.prev$contaminant, phy)

Create a tsv file of the relative abundance values for each species in each sample. This can then be transferred to other GUI-based programs for further analysis.

phydf <- phy %>% tax_glom(taxrank = "Species") %>% 
        transform_sample_counts(function(x) {x/sum(x)}) %>%
        psmelt() %>% select(OTU, Species, Sample, Abundance) %>% 
        spread(Sample, Abundance)

tax_fix_interactive(phy_subset)

Finally, create a relative abundance stacked barplot. Here, samples are ordered by Cohort and labeled with their name from the metadata column SubjectID. The plot is rotated so bars are horizontal. The 20 most abundant taxa are listed, and the rest are grouped as other. The plot is then exported as a .tiff image file.

phy_fix %>%
  ps_mutate(
    Cohort = factor(
      Cohort, levels = c("A1","A2","A3","B1","B2","B3"), ordered = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  comp_barplot(tax_level = "Species",
               label="SubjectID",
               n_taxa = 20,
               bar_width = 0.85,
               order_with_all_taxa = TRUE
               ) +
  facet_grid(
    rows = vars(Cohort),
    scales = "free", space = "free"
  ) +
  coord_flip() + guides(fill=guide_legend(ncol=1, reverse = TRUE, title="Species"))
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'seriation':
##   method         from 
##   reorder.hclust vegan

ggsave("speciesbarplot.tiff", device = "tiff", dpi = 300)
